MY INTEREST
What are they? How would you answer that? Female? Human? (other word)? It seems like a pretty (broad/question) question that you
wouldnt begin to know how to answer, but growing up, this is was a very clear question. a question my family asked each other a lot. What we
this was the shorthand (abbreviated) way of asking Whats their personality type?
This all started with
Ive had a fascination with personality for most of my life
My mom started learning about Myers Briggs when I was 5 years old and a lot of that knowledge was passed onto to me as it was something that
became an important part of all of our lives
It is something that I still use today and have gotten into the habit of trying to type people when I first meet them, or at least after getting a good
sense of what theyre like and what their thought process might be.
Not only do I just find it interesting and fun, but it helps me to understand why people do or say the things they do, and why a lot of things that we
might assume about people isnt true, its just a different way of observing the world and then different way of processing what we observe.
Why some people seem cold but dont understand why. Why some people are brutally honest (list a few)
(what makes people tick, what bothers people, what hurts peoples feelings. When something doesnt affect you the same way, it can sometime
confuse you. Whats wrong with this person? They need to calm down. Its not that big of a deal)
(why cant this person do or understand this thing thats so easy for me? They must not be very smart)
(why one person may want to go to go out and why another might want to stay home.
While some of these traits may appeal to some people and not appeal to others (ie, why we all like different kinds of people), there is not a single
bad personality trait and not one thats better than the other. Not a single personality trait that needs to be fixed or changed. Not one. (talk about
behavior/character vs personality?).
NO BAD PERSONALITIES - BUT PEOPLE THINK THERE ARE
We may on the surface recognize and agree that we all have different personalities, but subconsciously we dont look at them as their own dif
ferent personality, we look at them as deviating from our own personality. Often times when we see a person react to a situation differently than
we would, get upset about something we wouldnt, not enjoy the things we do, or as easily understand the things that we do, we interpret it as a
fault, not a difference. They must be missing something.
-not everyone is going to like every personality trait, why not everyone gets along, but they are all valid, none of them need to be fixed
the harmful effects of misunderstanding personality
-People would understand that just because someone doesnt do things the way they do it, have the skills they do, think the way they do,
doesnt mean theyre wrong. This has been the bane of my existence.
BIG 5 EXAMPLE
The most celebrated personality type in the US would be Extroverted Intuitive Feeler Judger
Personality trait most known
Whats interesting is that although I test low for Feeling(whatever the name) and Judging, I am an INFJ. I have only one characteristic off, but that
difference changes how I use and display these other characteristics.
And that goes for any combination* (make footnote about exclusion of neuroticm). All of these traits, are celebrated if they belong to an extrovert.
If an introvert has these traits, they dont display them in the same way. The Big 5 treats introverts as sad, empty shells (who would be happier if
only they were willing to work harder to reap those social rewards).

What big 5 is
How it judges personality (all characteristics are positive words)
Its perfect personality

If translating this into MBTI (ENJF), Im only one characteristic off from their perfect personality (INFJ). So if you were to translate it back into Big

Example: Big 5 shows clear bias, has negative personality traits
The one that gets to me most: lack of extroversion.
Bias towards extroverts (outgoing) what is it perceived as
Job interviews
Talk to customers. I have avoided going to places because the people talk to me too much
The Big 5 simplifies personality to the point that it has no meaning. It looks at the first layer of a person, their perceived behavior that they show to
the world, as a way to define their personality. It does not by any means go into details of why a person might display this behavior and explain
why its often not for the reasons you think it is.
Openness to experience - imaginative, open-minded, experimental
2nd
Creative, imaginative, adventurous, intellectual, unconventional, artistically inclined
High openness scorers are more likely to have a high IQ
Conscientiousness - conscientious, disciplined, efficient, well organized
2nd People who are low in conscientiousness are more likely to develop addictions of all kinds...
Reserved, formal, serious, quiet - Extraversion (Se) - outgoing, friendly, assertive, likes working with others
2nd Introverts tend to conserve their energy, and do not work as hard to earn these social rewards WORK AS HARD???!??!?!??!?!! People
who are low in extroversion do not experience the same high from these experiences, and so do not put in as much effort to pursue them.
Agreeableness - compassionate, eager to please, good natured
2nd
Low scorers tend to be hostile, competitive, and antagonistic
Neuroticism
A persons tendency to experience negative emotions
Certain personalities tend to develop more anxiety than others, but it is because their personality does not work as well with the societal system
that we have created as it does for other personality types. Its a similar reason why a person with autism is considered to be disabled, because
the way they think doesnt correlate with how the general population thinks, their minds dont work right because they dont work like the majority,
thus they are disabled. Societys system was developed by people, it is not a part of nature. Some personalities werent lucky enough to have it
cater to them. Being expected to think and behave in a way that is unnatural to them, leading to them doing it poorer than others, would under
standably cause some anxiety Excuse me, Neuroticism.

These are the misconceptions that the Big 5 has and spreads around. Most of the people you see in the world are strangers. Passersby. You
make a quick judgement about them from what you see in front of you. (If you believe that the person see in front of you is always an accurate
depiction of personality (rephrase), then the Big 5 would, more or less, be more accurate.) But thats not how personality works. Personality isnt
the behavior (that you project to the world) that most people see, its how you work in your head.
The big 5 could easily be (altered, skewed) due to mental illness. They actually include whats basically an indicator of mental illness or distress
as one of the 5 criteria that makes up a persons personality.
I dont initiate conversations with people I dont know. I dont care for small talk with strangers and wont put in the effort to keep the conversation
going. Just because I dont speak doesnt mean I dont have a lot to say. What does not having a lot to say imply? If you dont say what youre
thinking that you must not be thinking anything?
There is a clear bias towards extroversion. Because it doesnt even acknowledge introversion. An introvert, according to the Big 5, is someone
who lacks introversion. Neuroticism seems to have a lot of countering traits to extroversion. Introverts are just neurotic.
I got a 2 in extroversion. Im going out on a limb, but that might be because Im an introvert.
MYERS BRIGGS EXPLANATION OF BIG 5 ASSUMPTIONS
You are not on a scale of one (personality, cross out) trait (scale of extroversion, you do not lack intuition, you do not lack feeling, you do not lack
judging. You arent a deviant from one perfect personality. you are one of two different and equally (beneficial, good, w/e) personality traits that
make up your four-letter code.

shy/outgoing (before awareness)
-Before these words started being spread around (started entering peoples vocabulary), they were referred to as shy and outgoing
-There was a clear and (unabashed? ) preference for outgoing personalities
-when describing a person, shes friendly, fun, happy, outgoing! while shy is well, hes shy, but... But what? (No shame.)
-Nonetheless, it was exciting to hear the words introvert and extrovert more and more. Finally, people would understand.
- heard the phrase its where you get your energy - I couldnt believe it.
-When I heard the words, it was like hearing a language that only a few others spoke. I couldnt help but always listen in.
-however, I quickly noticed there was something wrong with the way they spoke. Sentences were structured oddly, verbs werent conjugated
correctly, and there was a very, very strong accent.
-Its clear nothing has changed. People know the words, but (never bothered to learn the language) dont speak the language.
Its not just about how quiet you are, its not even just about where you get your energy, its also about how you take in and process information,
and whether your other personality traits occur internally or externally
CAT/DOG
Are you a cat or a dog person?
Expecting an introvert to display happiness by going out talking loud and expressively with a large group of people is like expecting and cat to
show its happiness by running around a park barking and wagging its tail. Youre not going to see it.
cats/dogs comparison (cat people/dog people why is it that extroverts prefer dogs and introverts prefer cats. (as a stereotype))
Cats have resting bitch face. People naturally read their faces like they do human faces. Dogs have a welcoming face, either they have a big smile
or they give you sad puppy dog eyes.
A cat who goes off by itself, doesnt want to be held, etc., doesnt hate you. Trying to treat a cat like a dog angers it, it will distance itself from you
because it knows
Cats want peace. The first argument someone makes when they prefer dogs is always, always, always that they greet you at the door (and then
go on to list other traits that cats will also display if treated right. )
My theory is is that if someone owns/has owned a cat, and thats their first argument, theyre mistreating their cat. Their cat is depressed.
My theory is that if you treat a cat right, it will greet you at the door, it will sit with you, it will look for you just so it can sleep next to you because it
just wants to be near you, it will love you. Because it knows that its ok to sit in silence around you. Treat it like a dog, it will distance itself from
you. And a cat that gets no interaction is depressed.
(RUDENESS)
If a cat does not (reciprocate) the (misguided) love and attention you try to give it, and instead of changing your own behavior to better suit the cat,
you (obtain) a universal view that all cats are angry and boring, whos the one being (rude)?
If you smile and say hi to someone on the street and they dont even look at you, theyre not angry, they dont hate you, theyre not being rude.
They actually realize that theyre coming off as rude, and they dont enjoy it, but even something as small as eye contact, a smile, and a wave
takes energy. And sometimes we just dont have enough to spare. (Ive crossed the street because I just dont have the energy)
If youre talking to someone and
Iii. in social interactions, what is rudeness?
When you smile and wave at someone on the street and they dont even look at you, is that rude? If youre standing in an elevator and try to
make conversation and they dont (reciprocate), is that rude? If youre sitting on the bus and try to talk to the person next to you and they pretend
they didnt hear you, is that rude? Maybe. In some situations it could be, and youd never really know. But is it always rude? Is it even rarely rude?
In my introverted opinion, no.
WHAT DOES INTROVERSION FEEL LIKE (why we are rude)
a. A battery analogy. A conversation with a stranger takes up energy that we dont want to waste. When youre out of energy, the ache to
get home is unbearable. And the relief to get to an empty how is unbeatable.
B. Our home base is in our head. (explain the Myers Briggs type science) All Im saying is that theres reasoning behind peoples differences.
DISCLAIMER
I dont hate extroverts
My gripe isnt with extroverts. I love extroverts. Some of best friends are extroverts. I held a door for an extrovert once. In all honesty, despite my
introversion activism, I do tend to gravitate to extroverts more than I do introverts. If I wanted to up my preachy level to an 11 I could explain exact
ly why, because theres a reason.
I dont mean to insult extroverts. Im trying to bring them down to a middle ground to sit side by side with introverts. Silence doesnt have to be un
comfortable. Silence doesnt always need to be filled. A conversation to fill the silence can be just as uncomfortable for some people as it is for
others to sit in silence.
I prefer extroverts .. and go on..
it doesnt mean that an extrovert should have to constantly cater to introverts. They deserve to be comfortable as well, and so its hard for both to
win. And you cant always tell whos an introvert. I dont believe an extrovert is a terrible person for not walking on eggshells around an introvert.
All I ask is every now and then it you see a cat on the sidewalk, just let it be.
